{"source_key":"sha256-f88bd5c54ac5fbbfc982c6d403b2565f","record_index":98,"record_hash":"sha256:c3077c84ebacb9152fc9594a479c524043e8abfff6000991b9e2692e067c24d2","timestamp":"2026-05-24T14:21:39.363Z","kind":"tool_call","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:custom_tool_call","role":null,"text":null,"tool_name":"apply_patch","tool_input":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Update File: /Users/kiril/Documents/tars/Tars/02 Active/agent-session-capture/agent-trail.md\n@@\n ## Entry Point\n \n The first expected entry point is a pull request link.\n \n Possible GitHub placement:\n@@\n The simplest first version is probably a PR description or bot comment link.\n Check-run UI may be nicer later, but it adds product and permission complexity.\n+\n+## On-Demand URL Entry\n+\n+It would be useful if Agent Trail pages can be created on demand from an\n+existing forge URL.\n+\n+Example:\n+\n+```text\n+https://github.com/gitbutlerapp/gitbutler/pull/13936\n+```\n+\n+A user could replace `github.com` with a GitButler-owned Agent Trail domain and\n+land on a derived review page for the same pull request.\n+\n+Conceptually:\n+\n+```text\n+https://agent-trail.gitbutler.com/gitbutlerapp/gitbutler/pull/13936\n+```\n+\n+The backend would parse the forge URL shape, resolve the repository and pull\n+request, check whether it has access, then build or load the Agent Trail\n+overview for that PR.\n+\n+Access can come from:\n+\n+- the repository being public/open source\n+- the user authenticating with GitHub\n+- a GitButler or Forge installation having repository access\n+- a previously published trail snapshot with an allowed share policy\n+\n+This entry point should still respect the publication boundary. Rewriting a URL\n+should not automatically expose private captured context. It should create a\n+request for an Agent Trail, then show one of:\n+\n+- an existing published trail\n+- a newly generated review-safe overview, if access and policy allow it\n+- an authentication prompt\n+- a clear \"no trail available\" state\n+\n+On-demand generation is attractive because it avoids needing every PR to be\n+pre-linked by GitButler. It also gives reviewers a memorable gesture: replace\n+the forge domain with the Agent Trail domain.\n+\n+Open design questions:\n+\n+- Should on-demand pages be live views or immutable snapshots?\n+- Should generated trails be cached automatically?\n+- Who can publish or persist the generated result?\n+- What should happen when no captured agentlog data exists for the PR?\n+- How should GitHub authentication map to GitMeta/Forge access?\n \n ## Data Source\n \n Agent Trail should build on `but-agentlog` primitives:\n*** End Patch\n","source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-24T14:21:39.363Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"custom_tool_call","status":"completed","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]","name":"apply_patch"}}}